COMMENT 

  This program uses a USB Mouse to simulate a standard PS2 Port Mouse.  It does
    this by emulating the standard PS2 Port BIOS Functions
    (Int 15h, Functions C2xxh).  It does not virtualize the hardware IRQ 12
    and Keyboard Controller I/O Port functionality of a "real" PS2 mouse.
  This Driver should interface with any DOS (Int 33h) Mouse Driver that
    interfaces with the PS2 Mouse via the BIOS Interface.
    Unfortunately, many Int 33h Mouse Drivers (including those from Microsoft
    and Logitech) do not exclusively use the PS2 BIOS interface to access the
    PS2 mouse.  They instead access the mouse directly through the hardware
    (IRQ 12 and the Keyboard Controller I/O ports).
  There is a free Int 33h Mouse Driver, called CTMOUSE (Cute Mouse), that
    does use the PS2 BIOS to access the Mouse.  CTMOUSE and USBMOUSE work
    very well together.  CTMOUSE provides the same basic functionality as
    the Microsoft or Logitech drivers, but uses MUCH less memory (only about
    3.5k, vs 10~30k for Microsoft or Logitech).  I suggest you blow off
    Microsoft and Logitech and use CTMOUSE instead.
  Currently, there are two version paths of CTMOUSE: Version 1.9 and
    and version 2.0.  Version 2.0 allows the use of one Wheel, but (at least
    currently) uses direct hardware access, and therefore will not work with
    USBMOUSE.  Version 1.9 uses the BIOS functions provided by USBMOUSE,
    and works very well with this program.  Unfortunately, version 1.9 of
    CTMOUSE does not provide support for Wheel(s).  I have contacted Nagy
    Daniel, the author of CTMOUSE.  He has told me that would add a BIOS
    option to CTMOUSE version 2.0, but that has not happened yet (as of
    August 2004).  Nagy may decide to add native USB support to CTMOUSE
    version 2.0, instead of attempting to interface with the BIOS.
  I think it is better to use the BIOS interface, since it's hard to tell
    how many different types of mice there may be in the future (could be
    BlueTooth, FireWire, Bluetooth through USB, etc.).  Ten years from now
    there could even be some new kind of Bus architecture that doesn't
    even exist today that will be the "standard" way of attaching external
    devices to the computer.  Using the BIOS is a much more flexible way
    to do things, and will "future-proof" CTMOUSE to some degree.

END COMMENT ;

COMMENT 

  If the Mouse has Wheel(s) (most USB Mice have one Wheel), this driver
    emulates the Microsoft IntelliMouse protocols.  An IntelliMouse will
    return a Device ID of 0 after a Reset, just like a regular Mouse does.
    In this "standard" mode, the IntelliMouse always sends a packet of
    3 data bytes to the computer (just like a regular mouse does).
    The data does not include the Wheel, but does include pressing the
    Wheel as a third button (at least on some mice).

  By sending a special series of codes to the IntelliMouse, it will change
    and start using the IntelliMouse protocol.  In the IntelliMouse protocol,
    the Device ID is 3 (instead of 0), and the size of the data packet is
    4 bytes (instead of 3 bytes).  Of course, if the Mouse driver never asks
    for four bytes to be sent, then only three are actually sent even if the
    IntelliMouse protocol has been enabled.  The basic IntelliMouse protocol
    simply allows the addition of a Wheel, but doesn't allow for anything
    more complicated than that.

  There is also an IntelliMouse2 protocol (I don't know what the actual name
    for it is, so I will call it IntelliMouse2).  It is an additional extension
    to the IntelliMouse protocol, and allows a Mouse to have up to five buttons
    (instead of just three), and have two wheels (instead of just one).
    The Device ID returned by the Mouse is 4 (instead of 3 or 0) if the Mouse
    supports the IntelliMouse2 protocol, and the number of data bytes returned
    is 4, just as it is with the basic IntelliMouse protocol.  There is
    actually enough "space" in the IntelliMouse2 protocol to logically
    have up to seven buttons and seven wheels (as long as only one wheel is
    moved at a time), though "officialy" the protocol only supports 5 buttons
    and two wheels.

  This Driver supports both the IntelliMouse and the IntelliMouse2 protocols,
    though there is no DOS Mouse Driver around that can use either one of
    them, at least as provided by this program.  It's possible that CTMOUSE
    may add the appropriate support in the future, though it probably won't be
    the near future.

END COMMENT ;

COMMENT 

  This driver will handle mice with two to eight buttons, and with
    at most two Wheels.  Unfortunately, because of limitations in the DOS
    INT 33h protocol (as developed by Microsoft), only the first three buttons
    can actually be used for anything.  So, even if the Mouse has more than
    three buttons, the extra buttons will not be usable by any DOS programs
    until an appropriate Driver is written.

  CTMOUSE has developed an extension to the Microsoft standard that allows
    it to use a single Wheel.  The CTMOUSE extension still does not allow
    for more than three buttons, nor does it allow for a second Wheel.
    And, to be honest, mice with all those extra buttons and Wheels are
    not very common.  Hopefully, CTMOUSE will change this.

END COMMENT ;

COMMENT 

  In this version of the Driver, we do a VERY simple search of the USB
    Report Descriptor that comes back from the Mouse.  Basically, we
    assume the data is sent in the same order and same format as the
    data from a PS2 Mouse (1 byte of buttons, 1 byte of X Movement, 1 byte
    of Y Movement, and 1~2 bytes of Z (Wheel) Movement).  For a Mouse that is
    both USB and PS2 compatible (which many of them are nowadays), or mice
    that are compatible with the USB Mouse Boot Protocol (which they all
    should be), this will almost surely be the case.  It is definitely
    the case on the several different Wheel Mice that I used for testing.

  If there's a Mouse out there somewhere that sends the data with a
    different size or in a different order, this driver won't
    work correctly.  If that happens, we will either need to change this
    driver (making it "smarter" -- more general and more complicated),
    or come up with a special driver for that one particular mouse.

END COMMENT ;

COMMENT 

  As we are emulating the PS2 Mouse BIOS Function, there is an Option in the
    BIOS (actually, it's in the Mouse Hardware) to set the Mouse Sensitivity
    to 8, 4, 2, or 1 counts/mm (Mickeys).  In this Driver, we simply assume
    that the Raw data from the mouse is at 8 counts/mm, divide the Raw Data
    appropriately to compensate for the 8/4/2/1 counts/mm requested output.
    If the Mouse Hardware is not really 8 counts/mm (or at least pretty
    close to 8 counts/mm), the mouse will either be too sensitive or not
    sensitive enough without some additional adjustment.  On the several
    Wheel Mice I used to write and test this program, the resolution seems
    to be pretty close to 8 counts/mm.  They respond very similarly
    whether they are hooked up to the PS2 port or to the USB port, and also
    very similarly to a PS2-only (non-USB-compatible) Mouse.

  It is possible for the actual hardware resolution to be declared
    in the USB Report Descriptor.  It's also possible that a Mouse with
    a non-standard Hardware Resolution would somehow let you select or
    change the resolution so that it is standard.  On my mice,
    none of that is the case.

  This driver does not even look in the USB Report Descriptor for a declared
    resolution, or for a way to change the resolution.  So, even if it's there,
    it will be ignored.  In the future, this program may need to be modified
    to compensate for mice that do not have the "standard" 8 counts/mm
    resolution.  We may either need to do a more complete scan of the USB
    Report Descriptor, or we may need to add some additional command-line
    Option(s) to compensate for the hardware sensitivity, or both.
    The other possibility would be to build a special driver for the one
    particular "special" mouse.

END COMMENT ;

COMMENT 

  This program truly implements the plug-and-play opportunities allowed
    by the USB architecture.  Because of that, this program uses a LOT
    more memory than it would if it worked like most TSR's (including
    most of my other TSR's).  In order to preserve memory, a TSR normally
    will not install itself into memory unless the hardware it's trying to
    support, and any additional required support software, are already
    installed.  This program would be MUCH smaller if it took the
    "normal" TSR approach.  This program is VERY small compared to most
    TSR's (especially those written in a high-level language), but is still
    much bigger than it could be if the Plug-And-Play wasn't there.

  This program will continue to use the Plug-And-Play opportunites
    available to it, but somebody may someday want to implement a version
    that does not do that in order to preserve memory.  Such a TSR would
    require that a Mouse Actually be hooked up and Enabled on the USB Bus,
    and would not be able to automatically recover if the Mouse was
    disconnected while running.  Again, not as "nice" as this program,
    but would use a LOT less memory.

END COMMENT ;

COMMENT 

  It is possible to have more than one Mouse hooked up to the Computer at
    the same time.  This program supports that, and "ORs" all of the mice
    together so that they like like a single mouse at the BIOS Interface
    level (Int 15h, Functions C2xxh).

  If this program finds a PS2 Mouse already installed as it is being loaded
    into memory, it will OR itself to the PS2 Mouse that's already there.
    That way, you can use either the PS2 Mouse or any of the eight USB
    mice at any time.  You can also Disable (and, of course, Enable) any
    particular mouse from the command line if you want if there is one
    particular mouse that is annoying you for some reason.

  The way the mice are OR'd together is this.  Each time something on
    one of the mice changes, an IRQ is issued.  For the PS2 Mouse, it is
    always IRQ 12.  For the USB Mice, it is whatever IRQ(s) are associated
    with the USB Host(s) that the Mice are attached to.  This driver
    does NOT "stack up" several mouse-related IRQ issuances into a single,
    delayed "virtual IRQ", though.  Instead, this Driver lets each individual
    IRQ go through at the time it was originally issued.  What this Driver
    does, though, is to OR all of the buttons presses from all of the Mice
    together so that they act as a single set of buttons.  In essence, the
    mouse movements are handled and processed by each mouse individually,
    but the buttons are handled as a conglomerate.

END COMMENT ;

COMMENT 

  In Setting the Sampling Rate on the USB Mice, most of them have a Maximum
    Sampling Rate of 100Hz.  The BIOS (Int 15h) Driver allows for Sample
    Rates as high as 200Hz.  The Logitech Mouse I used to test this program
    does not work correctly with a Sampling Rate of 200Hz, so I suspect
    most, if not all, other Mice would have the same problem as well.

  In order to appear to be compatible with the PS2 interface, what we do
    is "pretend" to be Sampling at 200Hz when we are really only Sampling
    at 100Hz.  Basically, we lie about how fast we are really Sampling.

  Sampling at 100Hz is sufficiently fast anyway, and there's really no
    good, practical reason to sample any faster than that.  In fact, anything
    above about 60Hz doesn't provide any practical benefit that I can see.
    If somebody actually measures it, they will see 100Hz instead of 200Hz,
    but I bet they'll never be able to tell the difference in a practical way.

END COMMENT ;

COMMENT 

  In the Disable/Enable/eXchange Options, we do NOT verify whether a
    particular mouse (either USB or PS2) exists when we set the flags.
    We only check whether or not it is a valid Index.  This will let
    the user Disable/Enable/eXchange a Mouse that has not yet even been
    enumerated.  This, in turn, can let the user configure things
    from the command-line when this program is first installed in memory,
    and does not need to wait for the USB plug-and-play software to
    find and enumerate things.

  The reverse is also true.  The Disable/Enable/Exchange flags are preserved
    across all USB Mouse interactions (including Resets and Disconnects).
    This could potentially confuse the user, but hopefully they will
    be able to become un-confused if they look at the Program Status.

  Another confusing issue could be that the Disable/Enable/Exchange flags
    are stored by Mouse Index (a number), rather than by something more
    significant to the user (e.g., the second Logitech mouse).  Unfortunately,
    that's one drawback to plug-and-play with "generic" devices.

END COMMENT ;

