;SPACE AND CODE TO PROCESS OUR PROGRAM STACK
;  This code and must be physically at the END of the Program,
;    but must be one of the FIRST procedures called by the Program.
;  In addition, the Stack Pointer (SP) must be set properly
;    (to LastProgByte - 2) BEFORE this code is called.
;±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±

COMMENT 

  By default, DOS allocates all available conventional memory
    to a .COM program (like this one).
  We don't need all that memory, and in fact don't need more than the
    actual size of our program, plus some room for a stack.  DOS normally
    puts the stack at the very end of our 64k segment (DS = ES = SS,
    with SP = FFFEh).  If our program is relatively small (like this one
    is), there is a huge space between the end of our program and the
    stack that never gets used.  For most programs, this isn't a problem,
    since the memory is automatically deallocated when the program terminates.
  Howver, this program may end up needing to call a support program while it
    is running.  In preparation to do this, we will need to reallocate our
    memory requirements to free up some memory for the support program
    to use.
  Once we start using the default DOS stack, we will need to allocate to
    our program a full 64k of memory or the stack will get corrupted when
    we call the support program.  If we resize our memory before we
    start using the stack, however, we can reallocate to only the amount
    of memory we actually need.  This will leave more room for our
    support program to run in, and for any "sub-support" programs
    that it may use.

END COMMENT ;

;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
;RESIZE OUR MEMORY ALLOCATION TO THE MINIMUM SIZE NEEDED
;Inputs:  SP = LastProgByte - 2
;         ES = Local Segment
;Outputs: Rellocates Memory to the minimum size required to run the program
;Changes:
;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ResizeMemory:
  PUSH AX,BX  ;Save used registers
  MOV  AH,4Ah ;Function 4Ah (Resize Memory Block pointed at by ES)
  MOV  BX,(LastProgByte SHR 4) ;BX = Number of Paragraphs to Resize to
  INT  21h    ;Do it
  POP  BX,AX  ;Restore used registers
  RET

  EVEN 16
  DB (ProgStackSize/8) DUP ('PrgStack')

LastProgByte:
